\section*{Antigen-Induced Lymphocyte Proliferation}

In vitro proliferation of peripheral and bronchoalveolar lymphocytes to avian antigens has been assayed for diagnostic and research purposes [28,70]. Importantly, this test resulted to be positive in more than $90 \%$ of the recurrent and insidious cases of chronic pigeon breeder's disease where the presence of circulating antibodies may be negative [28]. Experiments also demonstrated that a positive stimulation index was usually 2.0 or greater.

\section*{Lung Biopsy}

Histopathological confirmation of the diagnosis is required in a number of subacute and chronic cases. It is critical that the pathologist is informed when HP is being considered; the findings are often subtle and must be interpreted with knowledge of the clinical presentation. This is particularly important because we now know that a relatively large number of patients with subacute or chronic HP may exhibit a different histological pattern, including nonspecific interstitial pneumonia [71] cryptogenic organizing pneumonia, or even usual interstitial pneumonia-like changes.

