\section*{Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)}

SLE is a systemic autoimmune disease with the capacity to affect every organ system in the body. The etiology is unknown, although hormonal, racial, genetic, and environmental factors have been implicated. SLE is primarily a disease of young women, with a female-to-male ratio of 9:1. Black and Hispanic subjects are affected more commonly than are white subjects; the prevalence varies worldwide and is approximately 1 case per 2,000 people in the USA. Antinuclear antibodies are present in the serum of virtually every patient with SLE, whereas antibodies to the Smith antigen and double-stranded DNA are more specific for the diagnosis. Classification criteria have been established by the American College of Radiology (Table 8.6); the presence of 4 of the 11 criteria is sufficient to establish the diagnosis.

